  "topic_name": "Light",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Light is a form of energy that enables us to see. Luminous objects produce their own light (Sun, stars, bulb). Non-luminous objects do not (Moon, planets). Light travels in straight lines. Materials are classified as: transparent (light passes through completely), translucent (some light passes), opaque (no light passes). Reflection is bouncing of light from a surface; plane mirrors produce same-size, laterally inverted images. Refraction is bending of light when passing between different media. Shadows form when opaque objects block light; umbra is the dark part, penumbra is lighter. Solar eclipse occurs when Moon blocks Sun; lunar eclipse when Earth blocks sunlight to Moon.",
    "rules": [
      "Luminous objects: produce own light",
      "Non-luminous objects: reflect light",
      "Light travels in straight lines",
      "Transparent: allows all light through",
      "Translucent: allows some light through",
      "Opaque: blocks all light",
      "Reflection: bouncing of light",
      "Plane mirror: same size, laterally inverted image",
      "Refraction: bending of light",
      "Shadow: umbra (dark) and penumbra (lighter)",
      "Solar eclipse: Moon blocks Sun",
      "Lunar eclipse: Earth blocks light to Moon"
    ]
  },
